## Common Cron Expressions

```ts
CronExpression.EVERY_MINUTE
CronExpression.EVERY_5_MINUTES
CronExpression.EVERY_HOUR
CronExpression.EVERY_DAY_AT_MIDNIGHT   // '0 0 * * *'
CronExpression.EVERY_DAY_AT_NOON       // '0 12 * * *'
CronExpression.EVERY_WEEK              // '0 0 * * 0'
CronExpression.EVERY_1ST_DAY_OF_MONTH_AT_MIDNIGHT

// Custom cron syntax: second minute hour day month weekday
'0 8 * * 1'    // Every Monday at 8:00am
'0 0 1 * *'    // First of every month at midnight
```

---

## Rules

- Cron tasks live in `src/modules/scheduler/tasks/` — never inline in services
- Every cron method must log start and completion with results
- Every cron method must wrap in `try/catch` and log errors — never let cron silently fail
- Cron tasks must be idempotent — safe to run multiple times without side effects
- For distributed deployment, use a lock (Redis) to prevent duplicate cron execution
- Heavy jobs (reports, bulk emails) should enqueue queue jobs — not do the work directly
- Never do unbounded queries inside cron (paginate or batch)

---

## Distributed Locking (Multi-Instance)

```ts
@Cron(CronExpression.EVERY_DAY_AT_MIDNIGHT)
async cleanupExpiredSessions(): Promise<void> {
  const lock = await this.redis.set('cron:cleanup', '1', 'EX', 3600, 'NX');
  if (!lock) {
    this.logger.debug('Cron skipped (another instance running)');
    return;
  }
  try {
    // do work
  } finally {
    await this.redis.del('cron:cleanup');
  }
}
```

---

## Forbidden

❌ Cron methods without `try/catch`
❌ Unbounded database queries inside cron (no pagination/batching)
❌ Heavy synchronous work directly in cron (enqueue instead)
❌ Cron tasks inside domain modules (keep in scheduler module)
❌ Missing start/completion logs
❌ Non-idempotent cron tasks
❌ Multiple instances running the same cron simultaneously without a lock
